Name: McBride, Sarah

The fight for fair leave isn‚Äôt just a matter of fair policy‚Äìit‚Äôs a matter of life and death. I know because I lived it. 

I held my husband‚Äôs hand as he took his last breath after his battle with cancer.

But through it all, we knew how lucky we were‚Äîthat we had the flexibility with our employer so Andy could get the treatment he needed, and so I could be by his side to support and care for him.

But I do not believe that in the wealthiest, most developed nation on earth that the time and ability to get and provide care that we had should be a matter of luck.

It should be the law of the land.

It's why I'm proud to have introduced the bipartisan FAIR Leave Act, ensuring that families who work for the same employer are entitled to the same job-protected leave as other workers.

Let's get it done.

Rep. Roy: ‚ÄúThe President ran on a very clear agenda and we want to make sure that we extend the Trump tax cuts, because every American deserves to keep more money in their pockets. 

But to do that, we've got to be responsible about what we're doing with respect to deficits. That means getting the spending down.

Name: Roy, Chip
text:
Rep. Roy: ‚Äú10 years ago our total spend was $3.6 trillion. Today it is $7 trillion‚Ä¶ If you want to save this country for our kids and grandkids, we're sitting staring at $36 trillion in debt. It will be $56 trillion even if I get everything I want.

So I've got to go fight to reform Medicaid so we can stop funding the able bodied, stop the blue state money laundering and restore fiscal sanity for the American people. 

If we do that, Trump will have the greatest economy ever. The SALT guys can get what they want. We can reform Medicaid. More vulnerable will be protected. There will be more health care freedom, and we will reduce the deficit. 

That's a win for everybody if we'll just do it.‚Äù

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 1765, Parliament passed the Quartering Act.

The act required American colonies to house British soldiers in barracks or, if needed, public buildings like inns and taverns. In Massachusetts, soldiers camped on Boston Common, leading to rising tensions and eventually the Boston Massacre in 1770. This would later inspire the third amendment in the Bill of Rights, which protects citizens from being forced to house soldiers in their homes.

Name: LaMalfa, Doug
text:
The House Agriculture Committee‚Äôs portion of the reconciliation bill passed out of committee, and it‚Äôs a huge win for rural America.

It includes a three-year reauthorization of the Secure Rural Schools program, which is critical for counties in Northern California where the federal government controls so much land that there‚Äôs no local tax base to fund essential services. SRS has kept schools open and sheriff‚Äôs departments running while Washington drags its feet on restoring the timber industry. This extension is a much-needed lifeline.

It also takes long-overdue steps to root out fraud and waste in the SNAP program by reining in the bureaucratic abuse that‚Äôs allowed states like California to hand out benefits to able-bodied adults with no work requirements and who don‚Äôt meet the federal requirements, all while taxpayers foot the bill.

The bill has improvements to agriculture programs as well, including making crop insurance work better. A working crop insurance program that protects farmers also reduces the need for supplemental disaster costs‚Äîprotecting farmers and taxpayers at the same time. We also improved programs for our specialty crops in California such as almonds, walnuts, pistachios, prunes, peaches, olives, and many others.

This is a strong step forward‚Äîsupporting those who truly need help, restoring fairness for rural counties, and bringing a little more common sense to Washington.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we shine a light on a Hometown Hero‚Äîsomeone whose service, sacrifice, or spirit reflects the very best of our PA-1 community.
 
But this week, we don‚Äôt honor just one. We honor every man and woman who has ever worn the badge to protect and serve our neighborhoods. Because every officer who puts on the uniform, every deputy who answers the call, every trooper who runs toward the danger, they are all Hometown Heroes.
 
National Police Week is a solemn reminder that behind every badge is a person willing to risk everything for someone they may never meet. A neighbor. A stranger. A child. A community. And in our community, we have felt that sacrifice deeply. Since 1898, sixteen of our own have laid down their lives while protecting Bucks County:

PA Deputy Constable Erwin Mondeau, 1898
PA Constable Henry Kolbe, 1914
Bucks County Sheriff Abram Kulp, 1927
Quakertown Boro Officer Edward Shearer, 1936
Dublin Boro Chief Eli Myers, 1965
Bristol Township Detective George Stuckey, 1972
Bensalem Township Officer James Armstrong, 1975
Bensalem Township Officer Robert Yezzi, 1980
Bucks County Deputy Sheriff Thomas Bateman, 1986
Bucks County Deputy Sheriff George Warta, Jr., 1986
Bucks County Ranger Stanley Flynn, 1993
Plumstead Township Officer Joseph Hanusey III, 2002
Newtown Borough Officer Brian Gregg, 2005
Middletown Township Detective Christopher Jones, 2009
Bucks County Ranger Thomas Booz, 2020
Warrington Township K9 Officer Stephen Plum, 2022
 
They wore different uniforms, served different towns, but shared a common mission: to keep our PA-1 community safe, no matter the cost.
 
Officer Brian Gregg, just 46 years old, was shot and killed by a drunk driving suspect he was standing guard over. Detective Chris Jones, just 37, was struck and killed by a drunk driver while conducting a routine traffic stop. Officer Joe Hanusey, just 30, a rising star, earned the Top Gun Award for most DUI arrests in Pennsylvania and poured his heart into Plumstead‚Äôs Youth Aid Panel, giving first-time offenders a second chance and mentoring our young people toward a better path. And Officer Stephen Plum, just 38, a proud U.S. Marine Corps veteran, died of a heart attack shortly after responding to a tense barricade situation; his final act was one of protection.
 
These men didn‚Äôt just serve‚Äîthey embodied what it means to be a Hometown Hero. Their memory lives on not only in our words but in our actions. So, please join our community this Monday, May 19, at 7:00 p.m. at St. Andrew Catholic Church in Newtown for the annual Bucks County Police Memorial Ceremony to celebrate their service and sacrifice.
 
And while we honor their memory, and the memory of all the PA-1 residents who wore the badge and gave their lives while serving other communities, we must stand with those still serving. Every day, our officers quietly sacrifice‚Äîmissing holidays, bearing unseen burdens, stepping into danger‚Äîbecause they believe in duty, community, and something greater than themselves. As a former FBI Special Agent, I‚Äôve seen their courage up close. I know what they carry‚Äîand I will never stop fighting to ensure they have what they need: resources, training, support, and the respect they‚Äôve earned.
 
And let‚Äôs carry that spirit forward. Let‚Äôs make every week Police Week. A handshake, a kind word, a show of support‚Äîsmall acts that remind our officers they are not alone.
 
To the families of the fallen: your loved ones are never forgotten. And to all those who have served or are still serving: we thank you and we stand with you‚Äîtoday and always.
 
May God bless our law enforcement officers, their families, and our beloved Bucks County.

I‚Äôve been abundantly clear:

I fully support President Trump‚Äôs agenda, including historic tax cuts for hardworking Americans.

Yet we must seize this rare opportunity to fully deliver major conservative wins.

For example, these include:

‚úÖ Addressing waste, fraud, and abuse in Medicaid.

‚úÖ Leveling the playing field in Medicaid and pay the same (not more) for able-bodied adults and the most vulnerable.

‚úÖ Eliminating the unconstitutional taxation on SBRs, SBSs, AOWs, and suppressors.

There‚Äôs no reason the federal government should pay states MORE for able-bodied, working-age adults on Medicaid than pregnant women, children, seniors, and disabled Americans on Medicaid.

It‚Äôs time for change. This is our only opportunity. We MUST act now!

Let‚Äôs be clear: most SNAP recipients already work, often in low-wage or seasonal jobs. SNAP helps fill the gap between paychecks and keeps people afloat when hours are cut or jobs dry up. 

Cutting benefits won‚Äôt make folks work harder‚Äîit‚Äôll just make them go hungry.

Name: Costa, Jim
text:
üßµFolks, a lot happened in Washington this week. But here‚Äôs something you need to know!

The House Agriculture Committee voted along party lines to cut $300 billion from SNAP over the next decade as part of Trump‚Äôs so-called ‚Äúbig beautiful bill‚Äù. I voted NO. Here‚Äôs why:

Name: Costa, Jim
text:
The proposal would push more costs onto states and penalize families for minor paperwork mistakes. 

It also forces parents of young kids and older adults, up to age 64, to work more hours just to keep food on the table. Rural communities would be hit the hardest.

Name: Costa, Jim
text:
In the San Joaquin Valley, the impact would be severe.

Nearly 30% of households in my district rely on SNAP‚Äîthe highest rate in California. These cuts would mean skipped meals, longer lines at food banks, and more families struggling to get by.

Name: Costa, Jim
text:
Every $1 in SNAP generates $1.50 in local economic activity. These cuts would hit grocery stores, truck drivers, and the farmers who grow the food we all depend on. 

Although we are the breadbasket of the world, hunger is real here at home.

Name: Costa, Jim
text:
This measure now moves to the House Budget Committee for final reconciliation, and it could get a vote by the House before Memorial Day.

I will continue fighting these cuts from becoming a reality. Food security is national security, and we must treat it that way.

As this article makes clear, delaying a Green New Scam repeal until 2029‚Äîor later‚Äîrisks locking these subsidies in permanently. Every year they remain, the green lobby gets richer, more established, and harder to defeat.

These subsidies are propping up Chinese industry at the expense of American workers. In 2024, solar accounted for 61% of all new U.S. electric generation‚Äîdriven by federal handouts. China dominates the global solar supply chain, so we are effectively using American tax dollars to subsidize Chinese manufacturing. Meanwhile, affordable, reliable U.S. natural gas and coal‚Äîand the jobs they support‚Äîare pushed aside.

Oklahoma is a top-five natural gas exporter. We know firsthand that grid instability, job loss, and dependence on China have no place in a Republican energy bill. We must repeal these subsidies ASAP‚Äînot in 2029.

Together with educators, cultural groups, and everyday citizens, they remind us that history lives on through the people who carry it forward.

Laredo is not just a border town. It is a borderland civilization. Name: Greene, Marjorie Taylor
text:
There is a lot of confusion about the big beautiful bill and understandably so.

If I had it my way, Congress would be forced to pass a balanced budget every single year and if we didn‚Äôt then we would not be eligible for re-election!

But clearly I don‚Äôt have it my way because Congress is a majority ruled legislature.

The big beautiful bill is a special type of budget called reconciliation that can pass the House by majority and Senate, meaning that it can pass in the Senate with 51 votes and not have to stand up under the 60 vote rule. And there are a lot of rules about what can go in and what can‚Äôt go in this reconciliation budget bill. I don‚Äôt make the rules. I‚Äôm just explaining it so that hopefully it helps you understand why it doesn‚Äôt contain things that I want passed immediately and should‚Äôve been done already in the House and the Senate like the very important DOGE cuts.

So we have three types of legislation that we can pass in the House that passes President Trump‚Äòs agenda. 

1. The reconciliation bill that Trump wants and named The Big Beautiful Bill. This is essentially an omnibus that prioritizes spending on border security, energy, and the tax bill. This will fund the federal government and prioritize spending to match policies that the Trump administration is asking the House and Senate to pass. It is going to be expensive and the White House is working closely with the House and Senate on what is in this bill. This is not a federal reduction bill, it‚Äôs a federal funding bill. If we don‚Äôt pass this, the tax law will expire and taxes will be increased by 65% on most Americans. It also funds two of our top priorities - border security and deportations and American energy and destroying the Green New Deal. Again don‚Äôt shoot the messenger, I‚Äôm just explaining it to you and not sugar coating it.

2. DOGE cuts also called rescissions. These can be passed separately or in one big package. Personally, I would like to be passing them every single week. I don‚Äôt know why we can‚Äôt pass DOGE cuts like defunding studies of the sex lives of shrimp each week. I think DOGE cuts are extremely important because this is how we reduce the size and scope of the behemoth, the federal government. 

3. President Trump‚Äôs Executive Orders. The House and the Senate can vote to pass legislation that would codify into law President Trump‚Äòs executive orders. He has now signed over 150 EOs. I would love to see all 150+ past. But if I were you, I wouldn‚Äôt get your hopes up that that will happen because after all this is Washington DC that never really does the well of the people. Sadly, and I‚Äôm just being honest not that I support that. I support doing the will of the people.

Here is what I am being told between the House and the White House. 

They told me that once we finish with reconciliation, President Trump‚Äòs big beautiful bill, that we will be passing DOGE cuts. OMB is going to send a rescission package to House Appropriations Committee. Again, I would like to be doing them every single week, but they are planning to do them in a package as far as I have been told.

Also, they told me that the executive orders will come through House committees. I don‚Äôt have details on the timing of that but will try to find out. 

Lastly, getting 218 Republicans to vote together is like herding cats. And it‚Äôs a lot more complicated when the Republicans, who never supported President Trump until the very end of the campaign when they had to because he was beating everyone, are all standing on their own little hills in their own little castles defending their own little kingdoms instead of fighting together.

And when spending bills are over spending instead of being a balanced budget a little bit over spending is the same as being a little bit pregnant. The reality is over spending is over spending. If there was a real fight for a balanced budget I would be leading it, and it would be worth it.

Until then, DOGE cuts!

Name: Houlahan, Chrissy
text:
Law(less)¬†+¬†(Dis)Order(ly) Episode 14

None of these actions make our country safer or citizens more prosperous, but here are some of the things the Trump administration delivered last week:

During a House budget hearing, Health and Human Services Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr. said "I don't think people should be taking advice--medical advice--from me."

President Trump worked hard trying to convince us that not accepting a $400 million plane from Qatar that he wants to use as Air Force One and then transfer to his eventual library would be dumb. Congress has to approve gifts to all Presidents but Speaker of the House Mike Johnson said this was "not in my lane."

After summarily firing the Librarian of Congress and then the head of the U.S. Copyright Office, the Trump administration is attempting a hostile takeover of the Library of Congress, a part of the legislative branch. Unknown to most people outside of the Washington bubble is the fact that the Library's sub-agencies are the ones that give confidential legal advice to members of Congress while also overseeing and preserving all copyrighted material in the nation. Trump and Elon Musk want access to that information and data.

We learned that the architect of Project 2025, Russell Vought, will be taking over DOGE when Musk's tenure as a special government employee expires. Vought is the same person who believes the nation is experiencing a "Marxist takeover" and promised to put career civil servants "in trauma."

American intelligence officials released a report confirming that the Venezuelan government is not controlling the Tren de Aragua gang's operations in the United States. President Trump's assertion the gang works in concert with the Venezuelan government and has invaded our nation is how he rationalized invoking the Alien Enemies Act. And the authors of the report were quickly fired by DNI Gabbard.

Falsely claiming a genocide against white South African farmers, President Trump granted refugee status to and flew a group of Afrikaners to the US on a State Department-chartered plane with plans to resettle them here using federal resources. The budget reconciliation bill - also known as the Big Beautiful Bill - is a major first step to extending the Trump Tax Cuts, unleashing American energy, and providing much needed funding and resources to secure our border. While it isn‚Äôt perfect, Congress must use the reconciliation process in order to pass it with a simple majority in the Senate instead of the normal 60-vote threshold. The budget reconciliation process has strict and complex rules, which prohibits us from including recision spending cuts.

In a perfect world, Congress would pass an annual balanced budget. Unfortunately, this isn‚Äôt the case. Congress has been addicted to spending and it‚Äôs taken decades of reckless federal spending to get us into this fiscal mess.¬†

Once we pass the Big Beautiful Bill, we must get to work on passing significant spending cuts outlined by DOGE and codifying Trump‚Äôs Executive Orders into law. This is the only way to get our spending addiction under control and put Wisconsin taxpayers first.

I look forward to my GOP colleagues coming together to pass the budget reconciliation bill so we can prevent a massive tax hike on the middle class, secure our border, unleash American energy dominance and start the process of reining in reckless federal spending.

text:
From @WSJ: ‚ÄúRoy and other Republicans say the current plan misses a rare chance to alter the nation‚Äôs red-ink trajectory by reducing spending on growing social safety-net programs. They want Medicaid work requirements to start sooner than 2029, as the current bill does. The spending hawks also want faster removal of clean-energy tax credits, which the current bill phases out over several years. They warn that the bill, as written, front-loads tax cuts in the next few years and delays spending cuts. That combination, they argue, means that budget deficits could be significantly higher in the short run.‚Äù

‚ÄúBrecheen is particularly focused on the clean-energy tax credits and wants them eliminated as soon as possible. He opposes the provision in the bill that keeps some partial credits in place for projects placed in service as late as 2031 and warned that lobbyists would push a future Congress to keep wind and solar tax breaks alive.‚Äù

We must address the solar and wind tax credits now. If they are allowed to linger, we risk our electric grid becoming entirely dependent on subsidized, unreliable energy. China manufactures most of the solar components we continue to use, meaning we are subsidizing Chinese industry. This threatens American jobs and displaces reliable natural gas.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
üßµ (1/10) Recently, SCOTUS was asked to decide whether district court judges can unilaterally stop the govt from enforcing a law or policy nationwide.

The court should jump at the chance to end universal injunctions.

Read my latest @FoxNewsOpinion:

https://t.co/UaUbyrZWig

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(2/10) Normally, a court‚Äôs injunction only applies to the plaintiff in the case.

But in the 1960s, judges began blocking the government from enforcing the policy against anyone, anywhere‚Äînot just addressing one plaintiff's concerns.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(4/10) At first, these universal injunctions were uncommon. Courts issued only 27 universal injunctions up until the 21st century.

But recently, they have become a fact of life.

Pres. Biden faced 14 universal injunctions in his 4 years. Pres. Trump surpassed that in 4 months.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(3/10) The universal injunction gives individual judges extraordinary power.

Don‚Äôt like a law passed by Congress? Gone.

Don‚Äôt like one of the president‚Äôs policies? Sayonara.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(5/10) Nowhere does the Constitution say that district courts have this immense power.

Yet judges around the country still claim they have the authority to bring the entire federal government to a screeching halt with the stroke of a pen.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(7/10) This gives courts little time to consider gnarly legal issues.

That‚Äôs why judges are able to shut down federal policies nationwide within days or even hours.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(6/10) To make matters worse, judges often issue these universal injunctions after preliminary hearings.

There‚Äôs no jury. There‚Äôs no trial. There‚Äôs no real testing of the evidence at all.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(8/10) Universal injunctions give virtually unfettered discretion to the country‚Äôs most extreme jurists.

The government could successfully defend a policy before 100+ district judges, but one judge who disagrees could still wipe out the policy nationwide.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(9/10) This isn‚Äôt an ideological issue. Justices Gorsuch, Thomas, and Kagan have all argued that universal injunctions short-circuit the judicial process.

Nor is this a partisan issue. Solicitors General for both Biden and Trump have asked SCOTUS to end universal injunctions.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(10/10) These individuals understand that the rampant use of universal injunctions by district court judges threatens to destabilize our entire system of government.

I hope the court will take advantage of the opportunity to end this unlawful practice.

Name: Spartz, Victoria
text:
Here is an example of how the provider tax scams work:

In a state, hospitals could agree to pay $10 million in provider taxes, and the state would increase Medicaid payments to hospitals by $20 million 

(not necessarily improving any benefits for the recipients - recently in IN $2.6B of Medicaid dollars were diverted by hospitals from the seniors in nursing homes).

Assuming the state had a 75% FMAP, the state would then receive $15 million in federal Medicaid matching funds (75% of $20 million).

As a result:

- hospitals would gain $10 million ($20 million in increased Medicaid payments minus $10 million in tax payments), 

- the state would gain $5 million ($25 million from the hospitals and the federal government minus the $20 million paid to the hospitals), 

and the federal government would pay  $15 million.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: This morning, I hosted a call between local, state, and federal officials to ensure Missouri receives the aid need to recover from this weekend‚Äôs tragic storms.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: In the call we discussed FEMA‚Äôs preliminary damage reports taking place this week which will kick start the federal aid process. And how the federal aid process itself works.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: I was glad to get representatives from the Mayor‚Äôs office, Governor‚Äôs office, the MO Delegation, and FEMA together so that we can work together on this process.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: Yesterday, Gov Kehoe sent a request for emergency disaster declaration. If approved, this disaster declaration would unlock millions in federal funds for immediate disbursement to help state and local activities related to the tornados.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: Beginning tomorrow, FEMA will begin preliminary damage assessments to evaluate whether the recent tornados are high enough to trigger Public Assistance, as well as Individual Assistance funding.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: Public Assistance funding is oriented to public entities, and can fund the repair, reconstruction, or replacement of a public facility or infrastructure, which is damaged or destroyed by a disaster. Individual Assistance is aid given to individuals following a disaster.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: Following the Preliminary Damage Assessment, FEMA will then relay those results to the White House where the President will make the determination regarding Governor Kehoe‚Äôs request for major disaster declaration.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text: This is just the beginning of the process and I am working with the White House, state, and local leaders every step of the way to ensure our Eastern Missouri communities receive the aid they need to rebuild and get back on their feet!

Name: Mace, Nancy
text:
Opening Remarks - Congresswoman Nancy Mace
Oversight Hearing: Surveillance in Private Spaces

Liberty begins with the right to close a door. A hidden camera kicks that door off its hinges.

The Constitution‚Äôs Fourth Amendment enshrines a ‚Äúreasonable expectation of privacy‚Äù. Yet today, that freedom is violated by secret cameras and hidden devices to record women and girls with impunity.

Freedom is not a theory; it is the right to breathe, to dress and undress, to sleep without someone‚Äôs camera filming your naked body. The Founders wrote liberty in parchment; hidden cameras erase it in pixels.

I speak not just as a lawmaker, but as a survivor. Starting on November 5, 2023, I discovered my former fianc√©, Patrick Bryant, had filmed women without their knowledge, without their permission and without their consent.

He filmed rape too.

He appeared to catalogue the footage in the way he saved the files. And he stored these images for years.

This isn‚Äôt just creepy. It‚Äôs criminal‚Äîbut only under weak state laws.

In South Carolina, first-time voyeurs face a misdemeanor and a small $500 fine. That‚Äôs not justice. That‚Äôs betrayal.

Real men guard a woman‚Äôs privacy; predators harvest it.

When predators install covert cameras or forge explicit images, they do not invade a room, they invade a life, and that life deserves more than a misdemeanor.

Exhibit 1: A screenshot of my naked silhouette‚Äîfilmed in secret. The camera sat silent, yet it screamed my safety was negotiable and my dignity disposable.

Exhibit 2: An image of the building where women were recorded. [Enter into the record the Deed and short term rental documents.]

Exhibit 3: Screenshot. Just one camera I found had 10,633 videos saved on it at one point.

Exhibit 4: Screenshot. Evidence Bryant was transferring data off his phone‚Äîthousands of files.

He seemed to have certain fetishes of the women he catalogued: as they stood at the end of his bed undressed, sexual intercourse I‚Äôm very specific places in front of his hidden camera, and in specific positions, while they were changing, genital areas of women at the beach and pool, and at least one rape victim while she was unconscious.

He would even save a headshot of the victim next to a series of images of their private parts.

He kept the images for YEARS. One series of upskirt photos, he saved for almost ten years.

Exhibit 5: Various images of women filmed and photographed without their knowledge, their bodies redacted to protect their identity. I discovered up to four recording devices.

Exhibit 6: Screenshot. Rape victim unconscious. (with her face blurred, and with her permission).

These weren‚Äôt accidents. They were premeditated. Planned. Filmed. Stored. Meticulously Organized. Categorized. Catalogued. Private hidden folder. For YEARS.

At least two potential victims told me they once saw one of his cameras and he denied he was recording.

I would learn after finding these images, and speaking to potential victims, Bryant allegedly raped atleast 3 women.

We face an enemy that records first and apologizes never.

When I spoke up, Bryant didn‚Äôt apologize. He retaliated.

In fact, Patrick Bryant has started the process of suing his victims. Myself included.

[Enter into the record 2 Preservation Letters redacting rape victims names and other names.]

So let me be crystal clear: I won‚Äôt be intimidated. And I won‚Äôt back down, not for myself, and absolutely not for the women he violated for YEARS.

Predators like Patrick Bryant don‚Äôt ask permission, and neither should justice. A hidden camera does not erase liberty and doesn‚Äôt deserve a slap on the wrist.

Justice also does not crawl out of a plea deal, it arrives in a sentence that fits the crime and restores the victim.

Justice should come in the form of real sentences, real fines, and real protection for victims.

That‚Äôs why I introduced:

The Sue VOYEURS Act, which creates a civil right of action for victims.

The Stop VOYEURS Act, which expands the narrow federal prohibition on video voyeurism.

Secret recordings thrive in the shadows. These bills drag them into broad daylight.

Liberty is not theory‚Äîit‚Äôs the right to undress in peace. To live unrecorded. Without being filmed while naked.

Let‚Äôs make sure the law reflects that truth. We need laws with teeth. We need survivors with standing. And we need to leave predators with nowhere left to hide.

Today, I choose daylight. I invite every member of this House to step into that light with me, to pass these bills, and to prove that in the digital age liberty still lives where Americans stand as our forefathers promised.

I encourage other potential victims to come forward. Potential victims may contact SLED‚Äôs lead investigator directly at: Haley Nelson, hnelson@sled.sc.gov.

A tipline also remains active with the Congresswoman‚Äôs office at 843.212.7048 for those who believe they may have been recorded, assaulted, or otherwise victimized by these predators.

I would run through a brick wall to protect women and girls in South Carolina.

To other potential victims, I want you to know, ‚ÄúI have your back.‚Äù

###

Elections sometimes come down to ‚Äúexceedingly, exceedingly, exceedingly‚Äù small margins.

These are illegal population numbers from Pew Research, as of 2022‚Äìand remember, they further exploded during Joe Biden‚Äôs presidency!
 
Pew estimated 1.4% of Wisconsin‚Äôs population is here illegally. The presidential race there was decided by a 0.8% margin.

In Nevada, 5.8% of the state‚Äôs population is here illegally. The last presidential race was decided by a 3.1% margin.

In Georgia, the estimate is 3.4% are here illegally. The last Presidential election was decided by a 2.2% margin.

In Pennsylvania the estimate is 1.8% here illegally. The last presidential election was decided by a 1.7% margin.

In North Carolina the estimate is 3% here illegally. The last presidential race was decided by a 3.2% margin.

In Michigan the estimate is 1.3% here illegally. The last presidential race was decided by a 1.4% margin.

Even if a small number of foreign nationals illegally vote in American elections, they nullify the votes of American citizens damage the entire process.

The House has done its job, now it is time for the Senate to pass the SAVE Act and secure American elections.
